{{Further|Tom Thomson}} {{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}} {{Use Canadian English|date=August 2018}}
[[File:Tom Thomson at Lake Scugog.jpg|thumb|Tom Thomson photographed by T. H. Marten on [[Lake Scugog]], 1910.]]
'''Tom Thomson''' (1877–1917) was a Canadian painter from the beginning of the 20th century. Beginning from humble roots, his development as a career painter was meteoric, only pursuing it seriously in the final years of his life. He became one of the foremost figures in [[Canadian art]], leaving behind around 400 small oil sketches and around fifty larger works on canvas.
Beginning his career in 1902 as a graphic designer, he only began to paint seriously in 1912 at the age of 35. His skills developed as he ventured through [[Algonquin Provincial Park|Algonquin Park]], sketching scenes that interested him. His creative peak came from 1914 until his [[Death and legacy of Tom Thomson|untimely death in 1917]]. His art style progressed from sombre, grey scenes into brilliantly coloured exposés, characterized by rapid and thickly applied brushstrokes. His later works presage the advances seen by the [[Abstract expressionism|Abstract Expressionist]] movement.
==Materials and working method== ===Sketch to canvas=== {{Multiple image | align = right | direction = horizontal | header = | header_align = | header_background = | footer = David Silcox has pointed to ''Opulent October'' as being a particularly striking example of the sketch to canvas transition.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|pp=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/key-works/opulent-october 35–36]}} The sketch (left) is dark-toned, utilizing muted greens, browns and other more sombre shades. The canvas (right) has the same composition, but uses "brilliant scarlets, light ochres, xanthine yellows and rusty oranges" to make the work into a "dazzling, dancing autumn subject."{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=182}} | footer_align = | footer_background = | width = | image1 = Tom Thomson Sketch for Opulent October.jpg | width1 = 300 | caption1 = ''Sketch for Opulent October'', 1915. 17.2 × 24.1 cm (6¾ × 9½ in). Private collection | alt1 = | image2 = Tom Thomson, Opulent October.jpg | width2 = 300 | caption2 = ''Opulent October'', Winter 1915–16. 54.0 × 77.3 cm (21¼ × 30{{resize|75%|{{frac|7|16}}}} in). Private collection | alt2 = }}
The artwork of Thomson is typically divided into two bodies: the first is made up of the small oil sketches on wood panels, of which there are around 400, and the second is of around fifty larger works on canvas.{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=181}} The smaller sketches were typically done in the style of [[en plein air]] in "the North," primarily Algonquin Park, in the spring, summer and fall.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|pp=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/significance-and-critical-issues/#canvases-versus-oil-sketches 59–60]}} The larger canvases were instead completed over the winter in Thomson's studio—an old utility shack with a wood-burning stove on the grounds of the Studio Building, an artist's enclave in [[Rosedale, Toronto]].{{sfnb|Silcox|2006|p=127}}{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|pp=181–85}}{{sfnb|Brown|1998|pp=151, 158}} Although he sold few of the larger paintings during his lifetime, they formed the basis of posthumous exhibitions, including one at [[Wembley]] in London, that eventually brought international attention to his work,{{sfnb|Dejardin|2011}} though the more plentiful sketches have typically been thought of as the core of his work.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/significance-and-critical-issues/#canvases-versus-oil-sketches 60]}}
He considered most of his sketches to be complete works in themselves and not studies for larger works, since in the transition to a larger canvas the works lose their characteristic intimacy.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/significance-and-critical-issues/#canvases-versus-oil-sketches 60]}} Still, a dozen or so of the major canvases were directly derived from smaller sketches. Indeed, paintings like ''[[Northern River (painting)|Northern River]]'', ''[[Spring Ice]]'', ''[[The Jack Pine]]'' and ''[[The West Wind (painting)|The West Wind]]'' were only later expanded into larger oil paintings.{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=181}} While the sketches were produced quickly, the canvases were developed over weeks or even months. Because of this, they display an "inherent formality," with the transition from small to large requiring a reinvention or elaboration of the original details.{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|pp=181–82}} In this transition he often exaggerated hillsides or other landscape features to give the final picture greater depth.{{sfnb|Murray|1999|p=110}} Comparing sketches with their respective canvases allows one to see the changes Thomson made in colour, detail and background textural patterns.{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=182}}{{sfnb|Murray|2006|p=92}}
===Materials=== In 1914 Thomson made himself a sketch box to hold 8½ × 10½ inch (21.6 × 26.7&nbsp;cm) panels.{{sfnb|Davies|c. 1930}} The lower half of the box served as a palette, while the upper half served as a support for canvas or wood panels. Slots made room for three paintings to be carried at any given time, keeping them apart so wet paint did not smear or flatten.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=123}} Thomson utilized different materials throughout his career, providing a method for dating paintings.{{sfnb|Murray|1999|p=25}} For example, the wood panels he used in 1914 developed vertical cracks.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=125}}{{sfnb|Murray|1999|p=25}} He had only occasionally used hard wood-pulp board in 1914, but consistently began using it in 1915.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=132}} In the spring and fall of 1915 he used [[Terra cotta (color)|terra cotta-coloured]] and [[Carnation (painting)|carnation]]-coloured paint as [[Paint sealant|sealers]], but by 1916 he had switched to [[ochre]] paint.{{sfnb|Murray|1999|p=25}} In the spring of 1917 he disassembled and cut up wood [[crate]]s to make into 5 × 7 inch (12.7 × 17.8&nbsp;cm) panels for sketching,{{sfnb|Murray|1999|p=25}}{{sfnb|Thomson|1917a}} smaller than those he normally painted on and requiring tighter handling.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|pp=141–42}} Fragments of brand names (e.g. Gold Medal Purity Flour, California Oranges) are stamped on the back of some,{{sfnb|Murray|1994|p=7}} such as ''[[:File:Tom Thomson Birches Spring 1917.jpg|Birches]]'' and ''[[:File:Tom Thomson Ice Covered Lake.jpg|An Ice Covered Lake]]''.{{sfnb|Murray|1998|p=85}} During the same spring he reused around one-third of his sketches, either because he was not satisfied with them or because he was short on painting materials.{{sfnb|Murray|1999|p=116}}
In 2000, a study was conducted to understand the materials and working method of Thomson.{{sfnb|Corbeil|Moffatt|Sirois|Legate|2000}} In 2002–03, before a travelling exhibition organized by the National Gallery of Canada and the Art Gallery of Ontario, the [[Canadian Conservation Institute]] utilized [[Infrared photography|infrared]] and X-ray photography, [[spectroscopy]] and micro-sampling of pigments to further analyze many of Thomson's paintings.{{sfnb|Webster-Cook|Ruggles|2002|p=145}} Sandra Webster-Cook and Anne Ruggles described in their research how Thomson applied differently coloured [[Primer (paint)|primers]] in various parts of his paintings to give them subtle yet important qualities.{{sfnb|Webster-Cook|Ruggles|2002|pp=145–46}}
===Photography===
[[File:Thomson 3567415.jpg|thumb|right|''A northern mill-yard, II'', {{circa|lk=no}} 1913-14. [[Library and Archives Canada]], Ottawa. Probably a view of the mill-yard of the abandoned Gilmour Lumber Company at [[Canoe Lake (Nipissing District)|Canoe Lake]]. The man seated on the stump is thought to be Tom Wattie, an [[Algonquin Provincial Park|Algonquin Park]] ranger.]]
Thomson occasionally used photography to capture things that gained his interest, such as fish he caught, images of his friends or the landscape. He does not seem to have used any of his photographs for producing art, with none of the extant photos corresponding to any of his paintings.{{sfnb|Reid|1971}} He instead preferred to capture images with small oil sketches, and nearly all of the works he produced are among these small sketches.{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=215}} David Silcox however has speculated that ''[[Drowned Land]]'' (and perhaps other paintings) may have been painted with a photograph as a memory aid given their "uncanny precision."{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/significance-and-critical-issues/#photography 63]}}{{efn|group=note|For more regarding Thomson's photographs, refer to {{bulleted list|{{harvp|Addison|Harwood|1969}}|{{harvp|Reid|1971}}|{{harvp|Silcox|2015|pp=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/significance-and-critical-issues#photography 62–63]}}|{{harvp|Silcox|Town|2017|pp=214–15}}}}}}
In 1912 while travelling up the [[Spanish River (Ontario)|Spanish River]] in the [[Mississagi Provincial Park|Mississagi]] area with William Broadhead, Thomson lost at least a dozen rolls of film (claiming in a letter that he lost 14 dozen) along with many more sketches after their canoe experienced several spills.{{sfnb|Thomson|1912}}{{sfnb|Murray|2002a|p=297}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#gathering-momentum 15]}} He had intended to bring the images back to Grip Limited and use them in his commercial work.{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=215}}
<gallery widths="165px" heights="165px"> E002712902-v6.jpg|''A lake in Southern Ontario, III'', {{circa|lk=no|1911}}. Library and Archives Canada, Ottawa|alt=A view, at dusk, looking across a marshy body of water or lake (possibly Lake Scugog or Rice Lake), with barnyard ducks, centre. In the background, on the far shore, are two large deciduous trees. File:E002852745-v6.jpg|''Scarborough Bluffs, II'', {{circa|lk=no|1912}}. Library and Archives Canada, Ottawa|alt=An evening view of Scarborough Bluffs, Lake Ontario, in Summer File:E008293726-v6.jpg|''Double exposure: northern lake, I'', {{circa|lk=no|1912}}. Library and Archives Canada, Ottawa|alt=Photo of two men (centre left), in the distance, paddling a canoe across a lake. File:E002852742-v6.jpg|''Two trout hanging from the tent pole'', {{circa|lk=no|1914}}. Library and Archives Canada, Ottawa|alt=View of a camp site, with a white tent, showing a string of fish and a fly fishing rod hanging from the front tent pole. File:E008293727-v6.jpg|''Miss Winifred Trainor, II'', {{circa|lk=no}} 1913-17. Library and Archives Canada, Ottawa|alt=Winifred Trainor in a plaid dress, standing and facing the viewer. She is holding a string of fish in her right hand and a fly fishing rod in her left hand. </gallery>
==Developments==
{{See also|Tom Thomson#Life}}
===Commercial art===
{{See also|Grip Ltd.}}
{{Multiple image | align = left | direction = horizontal | header = | header_align = | header_background = | footer = | footer_align = | footer_background = | width = | image1 = Gibson Girl by Charles Dana Gibson.jpg | width1 = 180 | caption1 = [[Charles Dana Gibson]], ''[[Gibson Girl]]'', {{circa|lk=no|1891}}. | alt1 = | image2 = Tom Thomson Study of a Woman's Head, Seattle.jpg | width2 = 180 | caption2 = Tom Thomson, ''Study of a Woman's Head'', {{circa|lk=no|1903}}. Tom Thomson Art Gallery, [[Owen Sound]] | alt2 = }}
[[Tom Thomson]]'s first foray into art came in 1901 with his education at Canada Business College in [[Chatham-Kent|Chatham, Ontario]]. It was there that he developed rudimentary penmanship abilities.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=113}}{{sfnb|Stacey|2002|p=50}} By 1902, he had been hired in [[Seattle]] at the design firm Maring & Ladd, working as a pen artist, [[Drafter|draftsman]] and [[Etching|etcher]].{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=113}}{{sfnb|Stacey|2002|p=50}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#early-adult-years 7]}} His main work there consisted in producing business cards, brochures and posters, as well as [[CMYK color model|three-colour printing]].{{sfnb|Stacey|2002|p=50}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#early-adult-years 7]}} Having previously learned [[calligraphy]], he specialized in lettering, drawing and painting.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#early-adult-years 7]}} Thomson may have also worked as a freelance commercial designer, but there are no extant examples of such work to confirm these suspicions.{{sfnb|Stacey|2002|p=51}} He was greatly influenced by the black and white illustrations he saw in magazines,{{sfnb|Stacey|2002|pp=47–63}} something especially apparent in his {{circa|lk=no|1903}} sketch, ''Study of a Woman's Head'', which draws inspiration from the "[[Gibson Girl]]" of American illustrator [[Charles Dana Gibson]].{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/style-and-technique/#diverse-influences 68]}} Thomson's younger brother Ralph wrote about Thomson during this period:
{{quote|[I had] a wonderful opportunity to observe his progress as a commercial artist and designer. He very often worked all night long while I watched him try one idea after another. The ones that did not meet with his approval he would either throw in the waste basket, burn up or smear with cigar ashes or the ends of burned matches. Others he would keep for a day or two but they would invariably meet the same fate. At that time he worked in pen and ink, water color and black and white wash. He was continually looking over the various magazines and giving the advertisements a great deal of study, principally from the standpoint of decoration. It was a regular game with him to pick the best of them, change the entire design to suit his own ideas, and then compare their respective merits.{{sfnb|Stacey|2002|p=51}}{{sfnb|Thomson|1946}}}}
After returning to Toronto, Thomson joined the artistic design firm [[Grip Ltd.]] in either 1908 or 1909.{{efn|group=note|Sources disagree on the approximate time of Thomson being hired. Grip supervisor Albert H. Robson wrote in 1932 that he was hired in 1907,{{sfnb|Robson|1932|p=138}} but by 1937 Robson was instead writing that he was hired in 1908.{{sfnb|Robson|1937|p=5}} Robert Stacey has suggested December 1908.{{sfnb|Stacey|2002|p=50}} David Silcox has suggested the beginning of 1909.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#graphic-design-in-toronto 9]}} Art historian [[Joan Murray (art historian)|Joan Murray]] has suggested December 1908 or January 1909.{{sfnb|Murray|2002b|p=310}} In curator Charles Hill's investigation, he noted that Thomson is listed in the ''Toronto City Directory'' for 1906–09 as working with Legg Bros. Photo Engravers, in 1910 merely as an artist living at 99 Gerrard E., and in 1911 as being at Grip Ltd. Hill supposes that this means Thomson likely began at Grip in late 1909, after the information for the 1910 directory was collected.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|loc=p. 113 n. 16}}}} The firm specialized in design and lettering work.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=113}}{{sfnb|Stacey|2002|p=50}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#graphic-design-in-toronto 9]}} Grip was the leading graphic design company in the country and introduced [[Art Nouveau]], [[Steel engraving|metal engraving]] and the [[CMYK color model|four-colour process]] to Canada.{{sfnb|King|2010|p=14}} Albert Robson, then the art director at Grip, recalled that when he first hired Thomson, "his samples consisted mostly of lettering and decorative designs applied to booklet covers and some labels."{{sfnb|Robson|1932|p=138}}{{sfnb|Rossell|c. 1951|p=3}}
[[File:Tom Thomson Advertising or Calendar drawing.jpg|thumb|''Advertising or calendar drawing'', Fall-winter 1912. Location unknown]]
The techniques he learned regarding Art Nouveau became apparent in many of his later works,{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|pp=94, 210}}{{sfnb|Reid|2002|pp=65–83}} including paintings like ''Northern River''; ''[[:File:Tom Thomson Decorative Landscape, Birches.jpg|Decorative Landscape, Birches]]''; ''Spring Ice'' and ''The West Wind''.{{sfnb|Stacey|2002|p=59–60}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/style-and-technique/#diverse-influences 68], [https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/style-and-technique/#commercial-art 71]}} Of particular note are the sinuous forms typical within the art style,{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/key-works/the-west-wind 47], [https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/style-and-technique/#commercial-art 71]}} seen in the "S-curves" of the trees which have their origins in Thomson's work as a [[Drafter|draughtsman]].{{sfnb|Stacey|2002|p=60}} Fellow artist [[A. Y. Jackson]] affirmed the [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]]'s tendency towards using Art Nouveau styles within their work, writing that, "We (the Group of Seven and Tom Thomson) treated our subjects with the freedom of designers. We tried to emphasize colour, line and pattern."{{sfnb|McKay|2011|p=185}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/style-and-technique/#commercial-art 71]}}
The senior artist at Grip, [[J. E. H. MacDonald]], encouraged his staff to paint outside in their spare time to better hone their skills.{{sfnb|Stacey|2002|p=58}}{{sfnb|Rossell|c. 1951|p=1}} MacDonald had perhaps the largest influence on Thomson's career as a painter; he enticed Thomson away from the commercial field and brought him towards painting through not only the encouraged weekend outdoor sketching, but through painting trips on holidays and introducing him to his fellow artists.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=117}} MacDonald himself credited William Broadhead with Thomson's emergence as a painter, writing in a letter to [[Arthur Lismer]] that "My memories in connection with Tom seem to begin with B[roadhead]."{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=118}} In a draft of an article, [[Harold Mortimer-Lamb]] similarly credited Broadhead with Thomson's emergence.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=118}}{{sfnb|Mortimer-Lamb|1919}} Lismer took exception to their claims, instead crediting MacDonald.{{sfnb|Lismer|1919}} A. Y. Jackson also expressed that Thomson's major development came after his ventures to Algonquin Park, rather than his time as a graphic designer.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=118}}{{sfnb|Jackson|1924}}{{sfnb|Jackson|1933}} Lismer later wrote, {{quote|[J. E. H.] MacDonald was the most important influence on Tom Thomson at this stage. These young artists (MacDonald, [[Frank Johnston (artist)|Frank Johnston]], Tom McLean, Frederick Varley, Franklin Carmichael and Lismer) worked hard all week and sketched on Saturdays and Sundays. On Monday it was MacDonald in his corner seat who gave his opinion on sketches and offered philosophical encouragement. He was already recognized as a Canadian artist. Thomson in 1911 had not tried his hand at sketching out of doors. Perhaps it was that hitherto he did not feel he could do anything with the medium of oil painting, or... he was not ready to emerge. It was in the summer and fall 1911 that Thomson first emerged as a sketcher. His first efforts were primitive. They had a child[-like] quality, but like a child's work, with good quality and character. It was in the country around Toronto, on the [[Humber River (Ontario)|Humber River]], in the bush near [[York Mills]] and on excursions into the country around [[Lindsay, Ontario|Lindsay]] and [[Lake Scugog|L<nowiki>[</nowiki>ake<nowiki>]</nowiki> Scugog]] where he and others went fishing that Thomson first painted.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=115}}{{sfnb|Lismer|c. 1942}}}}
<gallery widths="200px" heights="200px" perrow="5"> File:Tom Thomson Business Card.jpg|Tom Thomson's business card, {{circa|lk=no|1904}}. Tom Thomson Papers, [[Library and Archives Canada]] Tom Thomson Decorative Landscape.jpg|''Decorative Landscape - Blessing by Robert Burns'', {{circa|lk=no|1907}}. Private collection. Tom Thomson advertisement.jpg|''Advertisement for the Sydenham Mutual Fire Insurance, Owen Sound'', 1910. Tom Thomson Art Gallery, Owen Sound Tom Thomson Near Owen Sound.jpg|''Near Owen Sound'', November 1911. [[National Gallery of Canada]], [[Ottawa]] </gallery>
===Painting career=== ====First ventures to Algonquin Park (1912–13)====
{{See also|Drowned Land}}
[[File:Thomson, Drowned Land.jpg|thumb|''[[Drowned Land]]'', Fall 1912. [[Art Gallery of Ontario]], [[Toronto]]]]
It was in 1912 that Thomson's transition from commercial art towards his original style of painting became apparent.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#discovering-algonquin-park 10]}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2006|p=23}} This transition appears to have been instigated by his first visit to [[Algonquin Provincial Park|Algonquin Park]] in May 1912.<ref>{{plainlist| * {{harvp|Hunter|2002|p=25}} * {{harvp|Silcox|2006|p=20}} * {{harvp|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#discovering-algonquin-park 10]}} * {{harvp|Stacey|2002|p=57}} }}</ref> He acquired his first sketching equipment,{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=118}} but spent most of his trip fishing,{{sfnb|Hunter|2002|pp=25–26}} save for "a few notes, skylines and colour effects."{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=118}}{{sfnb|Jackson|1931}} Dating sketches to this trip has sometimes proved difficult.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=119}} One exception is the sketch ''Smoke Lake, Algonquin Park'', easily dated because Thomson gave it to Bud Callighen around the time of their first meeting.{{sfnb|Northway|1970|p=6}}{{sfnb|Addison|1974|p=75}}{{sfnb|Davies|1935|pp=35–36}} Charles Hill has also included the "somewhat awkward" ''Old Lumber Dam, Algonquin Park'' as likely being made during the trip.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=120}} Robson identified ''Drowned Land'' as being painted on the Mississagi Forest Reserve canoe trip.{{sfnb|Robson|1937|p=6}} Also dated to this time are ''The Canoe'' and ''A Northern Lake'' (1912).{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=120}}
<gallery widths="200px" heights="200px" perrow="5"> File:Tom Thomson Smoke Lake, Algonquin Park.jpg|''Smoke Lake, Algonquin Park'', Spring 1912. Tom Thomson Art Gallery, [[Owen Sound]] File:Thomson, Old Lumber Dam, Algonquin Park.jpg|''Old Lumber Dam, Algonquin Park'', Spring 1912. [[National Gallery of Canada]], [[Ottawa]] File:Thomson, The Canoe.jpg|''The Canoe'', Spring or fall 1912. Art Gallery of Ontario, Toronto File:Tom Thomson Northern Lake 2.jpg|''A Northern Lake'', Spring or fall 1912. Camp Tanamakoon, [[Algonquin Provincial Park|Algonquin Park]] </gallery>
In fall 1912 Thomson left Grip Ltd. to join another design firm, Rous & Mann.{{sfnb|Wadland|2002|p=95}}{{sfnb|Stacey|2002|p=58}}{{sfnb|Klages|2016|p=23}} Leonard Rossell went on to write, "Those who worked there were all allowed time off to pursue their studies... Tom Thomson, so far as a I know, never took definite lessons from anyone, yet he progressed quicker than any of us. But what he did was probably of more advantage to him. He took several months off in the summer and spent them in Algonquin Park."{{sfnb|Stacey|2002|p=57–58}}{{sfnb|Rossell|c. 1951|p=3}}
In October 1912 Thomson was first introduced to Dr. [[James MacCallum]], a frequent visitor of the [[Ontario Society of Artists]]' (OSA) exhibitions and [[The Arts and Letters Club of Toronto]].{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=119}}{{sfnb|MacCallum|1918|p=375}} MacCallum convinced Thomson to leave his position at Rous and Mann and commit to a career in painting.{{sfnb|Wadland|2002|p=95}} [[Lawren Harris]] later recalled Thomson's major developments around this time:
{{quote|Thomson began to develop. His work commenced to emerge into the clear Canadian daylight. His work had been tight and sombre, almost a grey monotone in colour. [[A. Y. Jackson|<nowiki>[A. Y.]</nowiki> Jackson]]'s sparkling, vibrant, rich colour opened his eyes, as it did the eyes of the rest of us, and Tom saw the Canadian landscape as he had never seen it before. It amounted to a revelation. From then on nothing could hold him.{{sfnb|Silcox|2006|p=212}}{{sfnb|Harris|1964}}{{Page needed|date=July 2018}}}}
MacCallum offered to cover Thomson's expenses for a year on the promise that he fully commited himself to painting,{{sfnb|Silcox|2006|p=21}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#discovering-algonquin-park 11]}} an offer Thomson eventually accepted after some initial hesitance.{{sfnb|Jackson|1933}} MacCallum wrote that when he first saw Thomson's sketches, he recognized their "truthfulness, their feeling and their sympathy with the grim fascinating northland... they made me feel that the North had gripped Thomson as it had gripped me since I was eleven when I first sailed and paddled through its silent places." He further wrote that Thomson's paintings were "dark, muddy in colour, tight and not wanting in technical defects."{{sfnb|MacCallum|1918|p=376}}
[[File:Tom Thomson Birches.jpg|thumb|''Birches'', Fall 1913. [[Hart House (University of Toronto)|Hart House]], [[University of Toronto]], Toronto]]
Thomson's ventures to the wilderness of Ontario were major sources of inspiration in his art, writing in a letter to MacCallum that the beauty of Algonquin Park was indescribable.{{sfnb|Thomson|1914}} His early works, such as ''Northern Lake'' (1912–13) and ''Evening'' were not outstanding technically, yet they illustrate a particular talent for composition and colour handling.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#thomsons-early-paintings 11]}} The sale of the former to the [[Government of Ontario|Ontario Government]] in March 1913 for $250 ({{Inflation|CA|250|1914|fmt=eq|r=-2|cursign=[[Canadian Dollar|CAD$]]}}) allowed him to spend more time in the summer and fall of 1913 sketching.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=120}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#painting-full-time 12]}}{{sfnb|Stacey|2002|p=60}} MacCallum described the painting as a "picture [of] one of the small northern lakes swept by a north west wind; a squall just passing from the far shore, the water crisp, sparkingly blue & broken into short, white-caps—a picture full of light, life and vigour."{{sfnb|MacCallum|1918|p=376}} Thomson's sketches from 1913 are often grey, but display greater colour handling than that seen in the earlier sketch of ''Northern Lake''.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#thomsons-early-paintings 11]}} Most of these sketches are simple with a far off shore.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=123}} Canvases like ''Morning Cloud'' and ''Moonlight'' use broken brushwork, a technique he likely learned from MacDonald and Jackson.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=123}}
<gallery widths="200px" heights="200px" perrow="5"> File:Tom Thomson, Northern Lake.jpg|''Northern Lake'', Winter 1912–13. Art Gallery of Ontario, Toronto File:Tom Thomson Autumn, Algonquin Park - fall 1913 - PCollection.jpg|''Autumn, Algonquin Park'', Fall 1913. Art Gallery of Ontario, Toronto File:Tom Thomson Morning Cloud.jpg|''Morning Cloud'', Winter 1913-14. Art Gallery of Ontario, Toronto File:Thomson, Moonlight 1913-14.jpg|''Moonlight'', Winter 1913-14. National Gallery of Canada, Ottawa </gallery>
====Colour and experimentation (1914–15)====
{{See also|Northern River (painting)|Spring Ice}}
[[File:Tom Thomson The Tent.jpg|thumb|''The Tent'', November 1915. McMichael Canadian Art Collection]]
Thomson often experienced self-doubt, with A. Y. Jackson recalling that in the fall of 1914, Thomson threw his sketch box into the woods out of frustration,{{sfnb|Davies|1935|pp=74–75}}{{sfnb|Jackson|1958|p=31}} and was "so shy he could hardly be induced to show his sketches."{{sfnb|Jackson|1917}} While his work from this period still displays "a certain awkwardness," Thomson surpassed his colleagues Jackson and Lismer in his brilliance of colour.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=127}} In a letter to MacCallum, Jackson wrote,
{{quote|Tom seems quite enthusiastic and I expect is quite an inspiring man to work with. You need a man with you who tries to do the impossible. To do what you know is easily within your powers never has given rise to a great school of art or anything else.{{sfnb|Murray|1999|p=34}}}}
The sketches produced in 1915 display his increasing tendency towards experimentation and his sensitivity to colour,{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=133}} experimenting with texture and colour in ways that his earlier subdued and precise work had avoided.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=127}} Beyond his work as a colourist, he developed a technique of presenting contradictory ideas that were simultaneously resolved within the same image. Typically he accomplished this by using the techniques of both [[Tonalism]] and [[Post-Impressionism]], later achieving it by joining decorative patterns with bold handling.{{sfnb|Murray|1999|p=70}} Jackson wrote regarding this period of Thomson's work, "No longer handicapped by literal representation, he was transposing, eliminating, designing, experimenting, finding happy colour motives amid tangle and confusion and [reveling] in paint. The amount of work he did was incredible."{{sfnb|Jackson|1919}}
Over the 1915–16 winter in Toronto, Thomson produced several canvases, including ''In the Northland''; ''The Birch Grove, Autumn''; ''Autumn's Garland''; ''Opulent October'' and ''Spring Ice''. The sketches of his work display a two-dimensionality. Thomson's work from this period—like the works of Harris, Lismer and MacDonald—became more decorative. The colour is heightened, with spaces flattened and forms arranged into vertical bands. The branches and trunks of trees are more stylized in nature.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=135}}
<gallery widths="200px" heights="200px" perrow="5"> File:Tom Thomson Soft Maple in Autumn.jpg|''Soft Maple in Autumn'', Fall 1914. Tom Thomson Art Gallery, Owen Sound File:Tom Thomson Tamaracks.jpg|''Tamaracks'', Fall 1914. Private collection File:Tom Thomson Approaching Snowstorm.jpg|''Approaching Snowstorm'', Fall 1915. National Gallery of Canada, Ottawa File:Tom Thomson Algonquin Park.jpg|''Algonquin Park'', Fall 1915. Tom Thomson Art Gallery, Owen Sound File:Tom Thomson Forest, October.jpg|''Forest, October'', Fall 1915. Art Gallery of Ontario, Toronto </gallery>
====Creative peak (1916–17)====
{{Further|Death and legacy of Tom Thomson#1917 sketching season}} {{See also|The Jack Pine|The West Wind (painting)}}
[[File:Thomson, Tea Lake Dam.jpg|thumb|''Tea Lake Dam'', Summer 1917. McMichael Canadian Art Collection, Kleinburg]]
In 1916, Thomson left for Algonquin Park earlier than any previous year, evidenced by the large number of snow studies he produced at this time.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=137}} He produced many sketches which varied in composition, though they all had vivid colour and were applied thickly.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#at-full-speed 16]}} Over the following winter, encouragement from Harris, MacDonald and MacCallum saw Thomson move into the most productive portion of his career,{{sfnb|Silcox|2006|p=20}} writing in a letter that he "got quite a lot done."{{sfnb|Thomson|1917b}} It was during this time that he produced many of what became his most famous works, including ''[[The Jack Pine]]'' and ''[[The West Wind (painting)|The West Wind]]''.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#at-full-speed 17]}}
In the last two years of his life especially, Thomson was particularly skilled in observing atmospheric phenomena, such as temperature, humidity, wind and light.{{sfnb|Silcox|2018|p=181}} Work from this period—such as ''The Rapids''—demonstrate his adeptness at controlling colour and are painted with a particular "crispness and freshness."{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=141}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#final-spring 17]}} Other paintings—such as ''Path Behind Mowat Lodge'' and ''Tea Lake Dam''—illustrate his bold and expressive brushstrokes.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|pp=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#final-spring 17–18]}} The scale of Thomson's later canvases foreshadow the Algoma canvases the members of the Group of Seven painted after the war.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=139}} [[Art history|Art historians]] David Silcox and [[Harold Town]] have described this period of Thomson's art as moving in the direction of [[abstract art|abstraction]].{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|pp=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#final-spring 17–18], [https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/key-works/cranberry-marsh 44], [https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/key-works/after-the-storm 52], [https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/significance-and-critical-issues/#the-group-of-seven 57], [https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/significance-and-critical-issues/#the-canadian-documentary-tradition 62], [https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/style-and-technique/#diverse-influences 68], [https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/style-and-technique/#an-idiosyncratic-palette 73]}}{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=148}}{{efn|group=note|For more regarding Thomson's later abstract tendencies, refer to: {{bulleted list|{{harvp|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/key-works/cranberry-marsh 43–44]}}|{{harvp|Silcox|Town|2017|pp=148–49}}|{{section link|Artistic development of Tom Thomson#Approaching abstraction}}}}}}
<gallery widths="200px" heights="200px" perrow="5"> File:Tom Thomson Winter Thaw in the Woods.jpg|''Winter Thaw in the Woods'', Fall 1916. Art Gallery of Ontario, Toronto File:Tom Thomson Autumn, Three Trout.jpg|''Autumn, Three Trout'', Fall 1916. Art Gallery of Ontario, Toronto File:Thomson, Spring Flood.jpg|''Spring Flood'', Spring 1917. McMichael Canadian Art Collection, Kleinburg File:Tom Thomson, Rapids, 1917.jpg|''The Rapids'', Spring 1917. Private collection File:Tom Thomson Northern Lights.jpg|''Northern Lights'', Spring 1917. Art Gallery of Ontario, Toronto </gallery>
===Approaching abstraction=== {{Quote box|width=20em|align=right|quote="At the time of his death a perturbed Thomson was poised at the crevasse between [[figurative art|figurative]] and [[abstract art|non-figurative art]]. Whether he would have survived the jump is a matter of conjecture; that he would have jumped is, to me at least, a certainty."|source=—[[Harold Town]]{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/key-works/after-the-storm 51]}}}}
Thomson was prolific in the number of sketches he produced—over four hundred across his entire career—providing an opportunity to observe the trends and progression of his style. Starting as a landscape painter, he drew away from typical landscape convention and began to experiment with more excited brushstrokes, clashing paint and more vibrant colours.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/key-works/cranberry-marsh 43]}} For artist and Thomson biographer Harold Town, the brevity of Thomson's career hinted at an artistic evolution never fully realized. He cites the 1916 oil painting ''Unfinished Sketch'' as "the first completely abstract work in Canadian art," a painting that, whether or not it was intended as a purely non-objective work, presages the innovations of [[abstract expressionism]].{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|pp=148–49}} Town describes the contents of the painting as being a sky that expresses the frustration Thompson must have experienced in adding paint to the small areas between trees, rocks and thickets.{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=148}} He similarly describes ''Late Autumn'' as being another "impatient study" that led to abstract experiment. Of particular importance are the areas between the branches, which are "brusquely smacked into place," as well as a similar foreground to that of ''Unfinished Sketch''.{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=148}}
[[File:Thomson Unfinished Sketch.jpg|thumb|''Unfinished Sketch'', Fall 1916. Private collection{{efn|group=note|The painting is on the reverse of ''Algonquin Hillside, Snow''.}}]] David Silcox has pointed to ''Cranberry Marsh'' as indicating Thomson's move towards abstraction.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/key-works/cranberry-marsh 43–44], [https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/style-and-technique/#diverse-influences 68]}} He has also viewed ''After the Storm'', likely one of Thomson's last paintings, as an indication that Thomson was already responding to the changes happening in Western art, even if he didn't exactly know where it would lead.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/key-works/after-the-storm 51–52]}} Examining the painting more closely, the landscape itself dissolves into bare strokes and pure abstraction.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/key-works/after-the-storm 52]}}
[[Art history|Art historian]] [[Joan Murray (art historian)|Joan Murray]] has expressed reluctance to describe Thomson's sketches as "abstract," given that some of them may have likely been intended as "colour notes for use in the studio," and because some of the sketches were unfinished.{{sfnb|Murray|2015|loc="From the Studio Building to Algonquin Park and Home Again"}}
<gallery widths="165px" heights="165px"> File:Thomson, Late Autumn.jpg|''Late Autumn'', Fall 1915. McMichael Canadian Art Collection, Kleinburg File:Thomson, Cranberry Marsh - summer 1916 - NGC 4698.jpg|''Cranberry Marsh'', Summer 1916. National Gallery of Canada, Ottawa File:Tom Thomson Algonquin Hillside, Snow.jpg|''Algonquin Hillside, Snow'', Fall 1916. Private collection File:Tom Thomson Autumn - fall 1916.jpg|''Autumn'', Fall 1916. [[Glenbow Museum]], [[Calgary]] File:Thomson, After the Storm.jpg|''After the Storm'', Summer 1917. Private collection </gallery>
